# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aws-cloudwatch
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aws-cloudwatch/alarm-device] An **alarm device** is a mechanism that gives an audible, visual, combination, or other kind of alarm signal to alert someone to a problem or condition that requires urgent attention.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/alarm-device] The word *alarm* comes from the Old French *a l'arme* meaning "to the arms", or "to the weapons", telling armed men to pick up their weapons and get ready for action because an enemy may have suddenly appeared.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/alarm-device] The word *alarum* is an archaic form of *alarm*.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/alarm-device] It was sometimes used as a call to arms in the stage directions of Elizabethan dramas.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/alarm-device] The term comes from the Italian *all'armi* and appears 89 times in Shakespeare's First Folio.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/alarm-device] Often explained as the off-stage sounds of conflict or disturbance, recent research suggests a bell or drum may have been used to rouse soldiers from sleep.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/alarm-device] Early alarm devices were often bells, drums, other musical instruments, or any items which made unusual loud noises that attracted the attention of the surrounding population.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/alarm-device] Whistles were used by police in the 19th century.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/alarm-device] Steam whistles have been used on locomotives, ships, and in factories as alarm devices.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/alarm-device] With the advent of electricity, a variety of other alerting devices have been invented, such as buzzers, klaxons, sirens, horns, flashing and coloured lights, and other all-purpose alarms.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/alarm-device] Alarm devices can be fitted to buildings as well as vehicles.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/alarm-device] Many buildings are fitted with fire alarms, ranging from a self-contained domestic smoke detector to a sophisticated alarm system that can operate building fire fighting systems automatically to extinguish fires with water or inert gases.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/alarm-device] Many industries have developed standards for alarm devices, and the colours red, blue and amber are generally recognized as alarm device-related colours, with flashing lights often indicating urgent conditions.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/alarm-device] Human reactions to an alarm will often depend on upbringing, psychological training, or the behavior of others in the environment.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/alarm-device] Consequently, the ability to test an alarm and hold regular drills to practice an appropriate response may be provided as part of an alarm system.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/alarm-device] Alarm devices that are intended to cause the evacuation of an occupied building, such as fire alarms, may be deliberately designed to make remaining in the space difficult or even painful in order to encourage occupants to leave.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/alarm-device] Some alarms may startle and cause a fight-or-flight response in humans; a person under this mindset will panic and either flee the perceived danger or attempt to eliminate it, often ignoring rational thought in either case.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/alarm-device] A person in such a state can be characterized as "alarmed".
[src:aws-cloudwatch/alarm-device] With any kind of alarm, people must balance between the danger of false alarms (called "false positives") — the signal going off in the absence of a problem — or an alarm failing to signal an actual problem (called a "false negative").
[src:aws-cloudwatch/alarm-device] False alarms can waste resources expensively and can even be dangerous.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/alarm-device] For example, false alarms of a fire can waste firefighter manpower, making them unavailable for a real fire, and risk injury to firefighters and others as the fire engines race to the alleged fire's location.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/alarm-device] In addition, false alarms may acclimatise people to ignore alarm signals, and thus possibly to ignore an actual emergency: Aesop's fable of *The Boy Who Cried Wolf* exemplifies this problem.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/alarm-device] A false alarm is one of the most significant issues with conventional alarm systems.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/alarm-device] They can be triggered for several reasons, such as the movement of pets, typing in the wrong security codes, or loud sounds from windows or doors.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/alarm-device] In the case of fire alarms, aerosol sprays, smoking, or burning food can all lead to a false alarm.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/alarm-device] Many avoid the risk of false alarms by ensuring their alarms are secured in an appropriate location, such as placing a smoke detector or fire alarm away from the kitchen where smoke from burned food or large quantities of steam which may trigger a false alarm are common occurrences.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/alarm-device] In the case of a security alarm, an additional monitoring station which assesses whether there is a legitimate need for help can reduce false alarms.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/application-performance-management] In the fields of information technology and systems management, **application performance management** (**APM**) is the monitoring and management of the performance and availability of software applications.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/application-performance-management] APM strives to detect and diagnose complex application performance problems to maintain an expected level of service.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/application-performance-management] The term monitoring was replaced by many tool vendors by the term Observability.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/application-performance-management] Often, monitoring is seen as the technical process of data collection, whereas observability is seen as the capability to understand a systems behavior.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/application-performance-management] Two sets of performance metrics are closely monitored.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/application-performance-management] The first set of performance metrics defines the performance experienced by end-users of the application.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/application-performance-management] One example of performance is average response times under peak load.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/application-performance-management] The second set of performance metrics measures the computational resources used by the application for the load, indicating whether there is adequate capacity to support the load, as well as possible locations of a performance bottleneck.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/application-performance-management] Measurement of these quantities establishes an empirical performance baseline for the application.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/application-performance-management] The baseline can then be used to detect changes in performance.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/application-performance-management] Changes in performance can be correlated with external events and subsequently used to predict future changes in application performance.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/application-performance-management] The use of APM is common for Web applications, which lends itself best to the more detailed monitoring techniques.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/application-performance-management] In addition to measuring response time for a user, response times for components of a Web application can also be monitored to help pinpoint causes of delay.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/application-performance-management] There also exist HTTP appliances that can decode transaction-specific response times at the Web server layer of the application.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/application-performance-management] Measuring application performance causes overhead, that might also influence the user experience.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/application-performance-management] The overhead can be reduced by several technical measures, including reducing the amount of monitored events and aggregation of data before serialization.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/application-performance-management] Since the first half of 2013, APM has entered into a period of intense competition in technology and strategy with a multiplicity of vendors and viewpoints.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/application-performance-management] This has caused an upheaval in the marketplace with vendors from unrelated backgrounds (including network monitoring, systems management, application instrumentation, and web performance monitoring) adopting messaging around APM.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/application-performance-management] As a result, the term APM has become diluted and has evolved into a concept for managing application performance across many diverse computing platforms, rather than a single market.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/application-performance-management] With so many vendors to choose from, selecting one can be a challenge.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/application-performance-management] It is important to evaluate each carefully to ensure its capabilities meet your needs.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/application-performance-management] Two challenges for implementing APM are (1) it can be difficult to instrument an application to monitor application performance, especially among components of an application, and (2) applications can be virtualized, which increases the variability of the measurements.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/application-performance-management] To alleviate the first problem application service management (ASM) provides an application-centric approach, where business service performance visibility is a key objective.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/application-performance-management] The second aspect present in distributed, virtual and cloud-based applications poses a unique challenge for application performance monitoring because most of the key system components are no longer hosted on a single machine.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/application-performance-management] Each function is now likely to have been designed as an Internet service that runs on multiple virtualized systems.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/application-performance-management] The applications themselves are very likely to be moving from one system to another to meet service-level objectives and deal with momentary outages.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/application-performance-management] Applications themselves are becoming increasingly difficult to manage as they move toward highly distributed, multi-tier, multi-element constructs that in many cases rely on application development frameworks such as .NET or Java.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/application-performance-management] The APM Conceptual Framework was designed to help prioritize an approach on what to focus on first for quick implementation and overall understanding of the five-dimensional APM model.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/application-performance-management] The framework slide outlines three areas of focus for each dimension and describes their potential benefits.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/application-performance-management] Measuring the transit of traffic from user request to data and back again is part of capturing the end-user experience (EUE).
[src:aws-cloudwatch/application-performance-management] The outcome of this measuring is referred to as Real-time Application monitoring (aka Top-Down monitoring), which has two components, passive and active.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/application-performance-management] Passive monitoring is usually an agentless appliance implemented using network port mirroring.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/application-performance-management] A key feature to consider is the ability to support multi-component analytics (e.g., database, client/browser).
[src:aws-cloudwatch/application-performance-management] Active monitoring, on the other hand, consists of synthetic probes and web robots predefined to report system availability and business transactions.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/application-performance-management] Active monitoring is a good complement to passive monitoring; together, these two components help provide visibility into application health during off-peak hours when transaction volume is low.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/application-performance-management] When preparing to implement a runtime application architecture, it is necessary to ensure that up/down monitoring is in place for all nodes and servers within the environment (aka, bottom-up monitoring).
[src:aws-cloudwatch/application-performance-management] This helps lay the foundation for event correlation and provides the basis for a general understanding of how network topologies interact with application architectures.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/application-performance-management] Focus on user-defined transactions or the URL page definitions that have some meaning to the business community.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/application-performance-management] For example, if there are 200 to 300 unique page definitions for a given application, group them into 8–12 high-level categories.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/application-performance-management] This allows for meaningful SLA reports, and provides trending information on application performance from a business perspective: start with broad categories and refine them over time.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/application-performance-management] For a deeper understanding, see Business transaction management.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/application-performance-management] Deep dive component monitoring (DDCM) requires an agent installation and is generally targeted at middleware, focusing on web, application, and messaging servers.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/application-performance-management] It should provide a real-time view of the J2EE and .NET stacks, tying them back to the user-defined business transactions.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/application-performance-management] A robust monitor shows a clear path from code execution (e.g., spring and struts) to the URL rendered, and finally to the user request.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/application-performance-management] Since DDCM is closely related to the second dimension in the APM model, most products in this field also provide application discovery dependency mapping (ADDM) as part of their offering.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/log-file] In computing, **logging** is the act of keeping a log of events that occur in a computer system, such as problems, errors or broad information on current operations.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/log-file] These events may occur in the operating system or in other software.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/log-file] A message or *log entry* is recorded for each such event.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/log-file] These log messages can then be used to monitor and understand the operation of the system, to debug problems, or during an audit.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/log-file] Logging is particularly important in multi-user software, to have a central overview of the operation of the system.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/log-file] In the simplest case, messages are written to a file, called a *log file*.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/log-file] Alternatively, the messages may be written to a dedicated logging system or to a log management software, where it is stored in a database or on a different computer system.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/log-file] Specifically, a *transaction log* is a log of the communications between a system and the users of that system, or a data collection method that automatically captures the type, content, or time of transactions made by a person from a terminal with that system.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/log-file] For Web searching, a transaction log is an electronic record of interactions that have occurred during a searching episode between a Web search engine and users searching for information on that Web search engine.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/log-file] Many operating systems, software frameworks and programs include a logging system.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/log-file] A widely used logging standard is Syslog, defined in IETF RFC 5424.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/log-file] The Syslog standard enables a dedicated, standardized subsystem to generate, filter, record, and analyze log messages.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/log-file] This relieves software developers of having to design and code their ad hoc logging systems.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/log-file] It can also be useful to combine log file entries from multiple sources.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/log-file] It is a different combination that may yield between with related events on different servers.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/log-file] Other solutions employ network-wide querying and reporting.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/log-file] Most database systems maintain some kind of *transaction log*, which are not mainly intended as an audit trail for later analysis, and are not intended to be human-readable.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/log-file] These logs record changes to the stored data to allow the database to recover from crashes or other data errors and maintain the stored data in a consistent state.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/log-file] Thus, database systems usually have both general event logs and transaction logs.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/log-file] The use of data stored in transaction logs of Web search engines, Intranets, and websites can provide valuable insight into understanding the information-searching process of online searchers.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/log-file] This understanding can enlighten information system design, interface development, and devising the information architecture for content collections.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/log-file] Message logs are almost universally plain text files, but IM and VoIP clients (which support textual chat, e.g.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/log-file] Skype) might save them in HTML files or in a custom format to ease reading or enable encryption.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/log-file] Instant messaging and VoIP clients often offer the chance to store encrypted logs to enhance the user's privacy.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/log-file] These logs require a password to be decrypted and viewed, and they are often handled by their respective writing application.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/log-file] Some privacy focused messaging services, such as Signal, record minimal logs about users, limiting their information to connection times.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/log-file] A *server log* is a log file (or several files) automatically created and maintained by a server consisting of a list of activities it performed.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/log-file] A typical example is a web server log which maintains a history of page requests.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/log-file] The W3C maintains a standard format (the Common Log Format) for web server log files, but other proprietary formats exist.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/log-file] Some servers can log information to computer readable formats (such as JSON) versus the human readable standard.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/log-file] More recent entries are typically appended to the end of the file.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/log-file] Information about the request, including client IP address, request date/time, page requested, HTTP code, bytes served, user agent, and referrer are typically added.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/log-file] This data can be combined into a single file, or separated into distinct logs, such as an access log, error log, or referrer log.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/log-file] However, server logs typically do not collect user-specific information.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/log-file] These files are usually not accessible to general Internet users, only to the webmaster or other administrative person of an Internet service.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/log-file] A statistical analysis of the server log may be used to examine traffic patterns by time of day, day of week, referrer, or user agent.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/log-file] Efficient web site administration, adequate hosting resources and the fine tuning of sales efforts can be aided by analysis of the web server logs.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/observability] The concept of observability was introduced by the Hungarian-American engineer Rudolf E.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/observability] A dynamical system designed to estimate the state of a system from measurements of the outputs is called a *state observer* for that system, such as Kalman filters.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/observability] Consider a physical system modeled in state-space representation.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/observability] A system is said to be **observable** if, for every possible evolution of state and control vectors, the current state can be estimated using only the information from outputs (physically, this generally corresponds to information obtained by sensors).
[src:aws-cloudwatch/observability] In other words, one can determine the behavior of the entire system from the system's outputs.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/observability] On the other hand, if the system is not observable, there are state trajectories that are not distinguishable by only measuring the outputs.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/observability] For time-invariant linear systems in the state space representation, there are convenient tests to check whether a system is observable.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/observability] is equal to n , then the system is observable.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/observability] The rationale for this test is that if n columns are linearly independent, then each of the n state variables is viewable through linear combinations of the output variables y .
[src:aws-cloudwatch/observability] Observability is a sufficient and necessary condition for the design of continuous-time state observers.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/observability] where ${\mathcal {C}}(\mathbb {R$ is the set of continuous functions from $\mathbb {R}$ to $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:aws-cloudwatch/observability] Since the system is observable if and only if $\operatorname {rank} ({\mathcal {O}})=n$ , the system is observable if and only if N is the zero subspace.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/observability] A slightly weaker notion than observability is *detectability*.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/observability] A system is detectable if all the unobservable states are stable.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/observability] Detectability conditions are important in the context of sensor networks.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/observability] Functional observability is an important concept because it determines the sufficient and necessary condition under which a *functional observer* (also known as a Darouach observer ) can be designed to asymptotically estimate $\mathbf {z} (t)$ .
[src:aws-cloudwatch/observability] Under certain conditions, functional observability and output controllability are mathematical duals, implying that the problems of estimating and controlling a linear functional $\mathbf {z} (t)$ (rather than the full state $\mathbf {x} (t)$ ) are equivalent under a system transformation.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/observability] where $\varphi$ is the state-transition matrix.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/observability] It is possible to determine a unique $x(t_{0})$ if $M(t_{0},t_{1})$ is nonsingular.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/observability] In fact, it is not possible to distinguish the initial state for $x_{1}$ from that of $x_{2}$ if $x_{1}-x_{2}$ is in the null space of $M(t_{0},t_{1})$ .
[src:aws-cloudwatch/observability] The system is observable in $[t_{0},t_{1}]$ if and only if there exists an interval $[t_{0},t_{1}]$ in $\mathbb {R}$ such that the matrix $M(t_{0},t_{1})$ is nonsingular.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/observability] Where $x\in \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ the state vector, $u\in \mathbb {R} ^{m}$ the input vector and $y\in \mathbb {R} ^{p}$ the output vector. $f,g,h$ are to be smooth vector fields.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/observability] Early criteria for observability in nonlinear dynamic systems were discovered by Griffith and Kumar, Kou, Elliot and Tarn, and Singh.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/observability] There also exist an observability criteria for nonlinear time-varying systems.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/observability] Observability may also be characterized for steady state systems (systems typically defined in terms of algebraic equations and inequalities), or more generally, for sets in $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:aws-cloudwatch/observability] Just as observability criteria are used to predict the behavior of Kalman filters or other observers in the dynamic system case, observability criteria for sets in $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ are used to predict the behavior of data reconciliation and other static estimators.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/observability] In the nonlinear case, observability can be characterized for individual variables, and also for local estimator behavior rather than just global behavior.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/system-monitor] A **system monitor** is a hardware or software component used to monitor system resources and performance in a computer system.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/system-monitor] Among the management issues regarding use of system monitoring tools are resource usage and privacy.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/system-monitor] Monitoring can track both input and output values and events of systems.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/system-monitor] Software monitors occur more commonly, sometimes as a part of a widget engine.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/system-monitor] These monitoring systems are often used to keep track of system resources, such as CPU usage and frequency, or the amount of free RAM.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/system-monitor] They are also used to display items such as free space on one or more hard drives, the temperature of the CPU and other important components, and networking information including the system IP address and current rates of upload and download.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/system-monitor] Other possible displays may include the date and time, system uptime, computer name, username, hard drive S.M.A.R.T. data, fan speeds, and the voltages being provided by the power supply.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/system-monitor] Less common are hardware-based systems monitoring similar information.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/system-monitor] Customarily these occupy one or more drive bays on the front of the computer case, and either interface directly with the system hardware or connect to a software data-collection system via USB.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/system-monitor] With either approach to gathering data, the monitoring system displays information on a small LCD panel or on series of small analog or LED numeric displays.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/system-monitor] Some hardware-based system monitors also allow direct control of fan speeds, allowing the user to quickly customize the cooling in the system.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/system-monitor] The primary function of a few very high-end models of hardware system monitor is to interface with only a specific model of motherboard.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/system-monitor] These systems directly utilize the sensors built into the system, providing more detailed and accurate information than less-expensive monitoring systems customarily provide.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/system-monitor] Software monitoring tools operate within the device they're monitoring.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/system-monitor] Unlike software monitoring tools, hardware measurement tools can either located within the device being measure, or they can be attached and operate from an external location.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/system-monitor] A **hardware monitor** is a common component of modern motherboards, which can either come as a separate chip, often interfaced through I2C or SMBus, or as part of a Super I/O solution, often interfaced through Low Pin Count (LPC).
[src:aws-cloudwatch/system-monitor] These devices make it possible to monitor temperature in the chassis, voltage supplied to the motherboard by the power supply unit and the speed of the computer fans that are connected directly to one of the fan headers on the motherboard.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/system-monitor] Many of these hardware monitors also have fan controlling capabilities.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/system-monitor] System monitoring software like SpeedFan on Windows, lm_sensors on Linux, envstat on NetBSD, and sysctl hw.sensors on OpenBSD and DragonFly can interface with these chips to relay this environmental sensor information to the user.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/system-monitor] When an individual user is measuring the performance of a single-user system, whether it is a standalone box or a virtual machine on a multi-user system, access does not impede the privacy of others.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/system-monitor] Privacy becomes an issue when someone other than the end-user, such as a system manager, has legitimate need to access data about other users.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/system-monitor] When events occur faster than a monitor can record them, a workaround is needed, such as replacing event recording with simple counting.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/system-monitor] Another consideration is not having major impact on the CPU and storage available for useful work.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/system-monitor] While a hardware monitor will usually have less impact than a software monitor, there are data items, such as "some descriptive information, such as program names" that must involve software.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/system-monitor] A further consideration is that a bug in this domain can have severe impact: an extreme case would "cause the OS to crash".
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Although the term commonly refers to wireless data transfer mechanisms (e.g., using radio, ultrasonic, or infrared systems), it also encompasses data transferred over other media such as a telephone or computer network, optical link or other wired communications like power line carriers.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Many modern telemetry systems take advantage of the low cost and ubiquity of GSM networks by using SMS to receive and transmit telemetry data.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] A *telemeter* is a physical device used in telemetry.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] It consists of a sensor, a transmission path, and a display, recording, or control device.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Electronic devices are widely used in telemetry and can be wireless or hard-wired, analog or digital.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Other technologies are also possible, such as mechanical, hydraulic and optical.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Telemetry may be commutated to allow the transmission of multiple data streams in a fixed frame.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] The beginning of industrial telemetry lies in the steam age, although the sensor was not called *telemeter* at that time.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Examples are James Watt's (1736-1819) additions to his steam engines for monitoring from a (near) distance such as the mercury pressure gauge and the fly-ball governor.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] In 1889 this led an author in the Institution of Civil Engineers proceedings to suggest that the term for the rangefinder telemeter might be replaced with tacheometer.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] In the 1930s use of electrical telemeters grew rapidly.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] The electrical strain gauge was widely used in rocket and aviation research and the radiosonde was invented for meteorological measurements.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] The advent of World War II gave an impetus to industrial development and henceforth many of these telemeters became commercially viable.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Carrying on from rocket research, radio telemetry was used routinely as space exploration got underway.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Spacecraft are in a place where a physical connection is not possible, leaving radio or other electromagnetic waves (such as infrared lasers) as the only viable option for telemetry.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] During crewed space missions it is used to monitor not only parameters of the vehicle, but also the health and life support of the astronauts.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] During the Cold War telemetry found uses in espionage.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] US intelligence found that they could monitor the telemetry from Soviet missile tests by building a telemeter of their own to intercept the radio signals and hence learn a great deal about Soviet capabilities.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Telemeters are the physical devices used in telemetry.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Telemetering information over wire had its origins in the 19th century.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] One of the first data-transmission circuits was developed in 1845 between the Russian Tsar's Winter Palace and army headquarters.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] In 1874, French engineers built a system of weather and snow-depth sensors on Mont Blanc that transmitted real-time information to Paris.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Michalke patented the selsyn, a circuit for sending synchronized rotation information over a distance.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] In 1906 a set of seismic stations were built with telemetering to the Pulkovo Observatory in Russia.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] In 1912, Commonwealth Edison developed a system of telemetry to monitor electrical loads on its power grid.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] The Panama Canal (completed 1913–1914) used extensive telemetry systems to monitor locks and water levels.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Wireless telemetry made early appearances in the radiosonde, developed concurrently in 1930 by Robert Bureau in France and Pavel Molchanov in Russia.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Molchanov's system modulated temperature and pressure measurements by converting them to wireless Morse code.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] The German V-2 rocket used a system of primitive multiplexed radio signals called "Messina" to report four rocket parameters, but it was so unreliable that Wernher von Braun once claimed it was more useful to watch the rocket through binoculars.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] In the US and the USSR, the Messina system was quickly replaced with better systems; in both cases, based on pulse-position modulation (PPM).
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Early Soviet missile and space telemetry systems which were developed in the late 1940s used either PPM (e.g., the Tral telemetry system developed by OKB-MEI) or pulse-duration modulation (e.g., the RTS-5 system developed by NII-885).
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] In the United States, early work employed similar systems, but were later replaced by pulse-code modulation (PCM) (for example, in the Mars probe Mariner 4).
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Later Soviet interplanetary probes used redundant radio systems, transmitting telemetry by PCM on a decimeter band and PPM on a centimeter band.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Although the two terms are closely related, telemetry and telematics are used differently depending on the field.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Telematics, by contrast, emerged later as a broader, more applied concept that combines telemetry with telecommunications, informatics, and digital fleet platforms.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] In short, telemetry is the enabling technology (remote measurement and data transmission), while telematics describes the integrated, digitalized applications that build on telemetry to deliver business, safety, and operational insights.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Weather balloons use telemetry to transmit meteorological data since 1920.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Telemetry is used to transmit drilling mechanics and formation evaluation information uphole, in real time, as a well is drilled.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] These services are known as Measurement while drilling and Logging while drilling.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Information acquired thousands of feet below ground, while drilling, is sent through the drilling hole to the surface sensors and the demodulation software.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] The pressure wave (sana) is translated into useful information after DSP and noise filters.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] This information is used for Formation evaluation, Drilling Optimization, and Geosteering.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Telemetry is used in modern motor racing, allowing race engineers to interpret data collected during a test or race and use it to properly tune the car for optimum performance.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Systems used in series such as Formula One have become advanced to the point where the potential lap time of the car can be calculated, and this time is what the driver is expected to meet.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Examples of measurements on a race car include accelerations (G forces) in three axes, temperature readings, wheel speed, and suspension displacement.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] In Formula One, driver input is also recorded so the team can assess driver performance and (in case of an accident) the FIA can determine or rule out driver error as a possible cause.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Later developments include two-way telemetry which allows engineers to update calibrations on the car in real time (even while it is out on the track).
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] In Formula One, two-way telemetry surfaced in the early 1990s and consisted of a message display on the dashboard which the team could update.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Its development continued until May 2001, when it was first allowed on the cars.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] By 2002, teams were able to change engine mapping and deactivate engine sensors from the pit while the car was on the track.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] For the 2003 season, the FIA banned two-way telemetry from Formula One; however, the technology may be used in other types of racing or on road cars.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] One way telemetry system has also been applied in R/C racing car to get information by car's sensors like: engine RPM, voltage, temperatures, throttle.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] In the transportation industry, a Fleet telematics system is used to provide information about a vehicle or driver's performance by collecting data from on-board sensors, such as a GPS tracking unit or a telematics control unit (TCU).
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] This is undertaken for various reasons ranging from staff compliance monitoring, insurance rating, fuel management to predictive maintenance.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] As part of an Intelligent transportation system, telemetry is used to link traffic counter devices to data recorders to measure traffic flows and vehicle lengths and weights.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Telemetry is used by the railway industry for measuring the health of trackage.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] This permits optimized and focused predictive and preventative maintenance.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Typically this is done with specialized trains, such as the New Measurement Train used in the United Kingdom by Network Rail, which can check for track defects, such as problems with gauge, and deformations in the rail.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Japan uses similar, but quicker trains, nicknamed Doctor Yellow.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Such trains, besides checking the tracks, can also verify whether or not there are any problems with the overhead power supply (catenary), where it is installed.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Dedicated rail inspection companies, such as Sperry Rail, have their own customized rail cars and rail-wheel equipped trucks, that use a variety of methods, including lasers, ultrasound, and induction (measuring resulting magnetic fields from running electricity into rails) to find any defects.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Most activities related to healthy crops and good yields depend on timely availability of weather and soil data.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Therefore, wireless weather stations play a major role in disease prevention and precision irrigation.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Because local micro-climates can vary significantly, such data needs to come from within the crop.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Monitoring stations usually transmit data back by terrestrial radio, although occasionally satellite systems are used.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Solar power is often employed to make the station independent of the power grid.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Telemetry is used in water management, including water quality and stream gauging functions.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Major applications include AMR (automatic meter reading), groundwater monitoring, leak detection in distribution pipelines and equipment surveillance.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Having data available in almost real time allows quick reactions to events in the field.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Telemetry control allows engineers to intervene with assets such as pumps and by remotely switching pumps on or off depending on the circumstances.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Telemetry is used in complex systems such as missiles, RPVs, spacecraft, oil rigs, and chemical plants since it allows the automatic monitoring, alerting, and record-keeping necessary for efficient and safe operation.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Space agencies such as NASA, ISRO, the European Space Agency (ESA), and other agencies use telemetry and/or telecommand systems to collect data from spacecraft and satellites.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Telemetry is used in the development of missiles, satellites and aircraft because the system might be destroyed during or after the test.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Engineers need critical system parameters to analyze (and improve) the performance of the system.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] In the absence of telemetry, this data would often be unavailable.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Telemetry is used by crewed or uncrewed spacecraft for data transmission.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Distances of more than 25.1 billion kilometers (May 2025) have been covered, e.g., by Voyager 1.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] In rocketry, telemetry equipment forms an integral part of the rocket range assets used to monitor the position and health of a launch vehicle to determine range safety flight termination criteria (Range purpose is for public safety).
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Problems include the extreme environment (temperature, acceleration and vibration), the energy supply, antenna alignment and (at long distances, e.g., in spaceflight) signal travel time.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Today nearly every type of aircraft, missiles, or spacecraft carries a wireless telemetry system as it is tested.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Aeronautical mobile telemetry is used for the safety of the pilots and persons on the ground during flight tests.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Telemetry from an on-board flight test instrumentation system is the primary source of real-time measurement and status information transmitted during the testing of crewed and uncrewed aircraft.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Intercepted telemetry was an important source of intelligence for the United States and UK when Soviet missiles were tested; for this purpose, the United States operated a listening post in Iran.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Eventually, the Russians discovered the United States intelligence-gathering network and encrypted their missile-test telemetry signals.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Telemetry was also a source for the Soviets, who operated listening ships in Cardigan Bay to eavesdrop on UK missile tests performed in the area.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] In factories, buildings and houses, energy consumption of systems such as HVAC are monitored at multiple locations; related parameters (e.g., temperature) are sent via wireless telemetry to a central location.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] The information is collected and processed, enabling the most efficient use of energy.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Such systems also facilitate predictive maintenance.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Many resources need to be distributed over wide areas.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Telemetry is useful in these cases, since it allows the logistics system to channel resources where they are needed, as well as provide security for those assets; principal examples of this are dry goods, fluids, and granular bulk solids.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] This facilitates knowledge of their location, and can record their status and disposition, as when merchandise with barcode labels is scanned through a checkout reader at point-of-sale systems in a retail store.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Stationary or hand-held barcode RFID scanners or Optical reader with remote communications, can be used to expedite inventory tracking and counting in stores, warehouses, shipping terminals, transportation carriers and factories.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Fluids stored in tanks are a principal object of constant commercial telemetry.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Telemetry is used to communicate the variable measurements of flow and tank level sensors detecting fluid movements and/or volumes by pneumatic, hydrostatic, or differential pressure; tank-confined ultrasonic, radar or Doppler effect echoes; or mechanical or magnetic sensors.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Telemetry of bulk solids is common for tracking and reporting the volume status and condition of grain and livestock feed bins, powdered or granular food, powders and pellets for manufacturing, sand and gravel, and other granular bulk solids.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] While technology associated with fluid tank monitoring also applies, in part, to granular bulk solids, reporting of overall container weight, or other gross characteristics and conditions, are sometimes required, owing to bulk solids' more complex and variable physical characteristics.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Telemetry is used for patients (biotelemetry) who are at risk of abnormal heart activity, generally in a coronary care unit.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Telemetry specialists are sometimes used to monitor many patients within a hospital.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Such patients are outfitted with measuring, recording and transmitting devices.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] A data log can be useful in diagnosis of the patient's condition by doctors.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] An alerting function can alert nurses if the patient is suffering from an acute (or dangerous) condition.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Systems are available in medical-surgical nursing for monitoring to rule out a heart condition, or to monitor a response to antiarrhythmic medications such as amiodarone.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] A new and emerging application for telemetry is in the field of neurophysiology, or neurotelemetry.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Neurophysiology is the study of the central and peripheral nervous systems through the recording of bioelectrical activity, whether spontaneous or stimulated.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] In neurotelemetry (NT) the electroencephalogram (EEG) of a patient is monitored remotely by a registered EEG technologist using advanced communication software.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] The goal of neurotelemetry is to recognize a decline in a patient's condition before physical signs and symptoms are present.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Neurotelemetry is synonymous with real-time continuous video EEG monitoring and has application in the epilepsy monitoring unit, neuro ICU, pediatric ICU and newborn ICU.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Due to the labor-intensive nature of continuous EEG monitoring NT is typically done in the larger academic teaching hospitals using in-house programs that include R.EEG Technologists, IT support staff, neurologist and neurophysiologist and monitoring support personnel.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Modern microprocessor speeds, software algorithms and video data compression allow hospitals to centrally record and monitor continuous digital EEGs of multiple critically ill patients simultaneously.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Neurotelemetry and continuous EEG monitoring provides dynamic information about brain function that permits early detection of changes in neurologic status, which is especially useful when the clinical examination is limited.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Telemetry is used to study wildlife, and has been useful for monitoring threatened species at the individual level.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Animals under study can be outfitted with instrumentation tags, which include sensors that measure temperature, diving depth and duration (for marine animals), speed and location (using GPS or Argos packages).
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Telemetry tags can give researchers information about animal behavior, functions, and their environment.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] This information is then either stored (with archival tags) or the tags can send (or transmit) their information to a satellite or handheld receiving device.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Capturing and marking wild animals can put them at some risk, so it is important to minimize these impacts.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] At a 2005 workshop in Las Vegas, a seminar noted the introduction of telemetry equipment which would allow vending machines to communicate sales and inventory data to a route truck or to a headquarters.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] This data could be used for a variety of purposes, such as eliminating the need for drivers to make a first trip to see which items needed to be restocked before delivering the inventory.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Retailers also use RFID tags to track inventory and prevent shoplifting.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Most of these tags passively respond to RFID readers (e.g., at the cashier), but active RFID tags are available which periodically transmit location information to a base station.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] A telemetry-based Tracking system is useful for tracking persons and property in law enforcement.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] An ankle collar worn by convicts on probation can warn authorities if a person violates the terms of his or her parole, such as by straying from authorized boundaries or visiting an unauthorized location.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Telemetry has also enabled bait cars, where law enforcement can rig a car with cameras and tracking equipment and leave it somewhere they expect it to be stolen.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] When stolen the telemetry equipment reports the location of the vehicle, enabling a Stolen vehicle recovery process where law enforcement can deactivate the engine and lock the doors when it is stopped by responding officers.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] In some countries, telemetry is used to measure the amount of electrical energy consumed.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] The electricity meter communicates with a concentrator, and the latter sends the information through GPRS or GSM to the energy provider's server.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Telemetry is also used for the remote monitoring of substations and their equipment.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] For data transmission, phase line carrier systems operating on frequencies between 30 and 400 kHz are sometimes used.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] In falconry, "telemetry" means a small radio transmitter carried by a bird of prey that will allow the bird's owner to track it when it is out of sight.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Telemetry is used in testing hostile environments which are dangerous to humans.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Examples include munitions storage facilities, radioactive sites, volcanoes, deep sea, and outer space.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Telemetry is used in many battery operated wireless systems to inform monitoring personnel when the battery power is reaching a low point and the end item needs fresh batteries.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] In the mining industry, telemetry serves two main purposes: the measurement of key parameters from mining equipment and the monitoring of safety practices.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] The information provided by the collection and analysis of key parameters allows for root-cause identification of inefficient operations, unsafe practices and incorrect equipment usage for maximizing productivity and safety.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Further applications of the technology allow for sharing knowledge and best practices across the organization.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] In software, telemetry is used to gather data on the use and performance of applications and application components, e.g. how often certain features are used, measurements of start-up time and processing time, hardware, application crashes, and general usage statistics and/or user behavior.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] In some cases, very detailed data is reported like individual window metrics, counts of used features, and individual function timings.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] This kind of telemetry can be useful to software developers to receive data from a wide variety of endpoints that can't possibly all be tested in-house, as well as getting data on the popularity of certain features and whether they should be given priority or be considered for removal.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] Due to concerns about privacy since software telemetry can easily be used to profile users, telemetry in user software is often user choice, commonly presented as an opt-out feature (requiring explicit user action to disable it) or user choice during the software installation process.
[src:aws-cloudwatch/telemetry] As in other telecommunications fields, international standards exist for telemetry equipment and software.
